\section{Generation of MATH: Precalculus}
\label{sec:generation-MATH-Precalculus}

\begin{longtable}{|l|p{8cm}|p{8cm}|} 
\caption{New questions generated from Precalculus questions in the MATH dataset, and the closest question among the existing questions.}\\
\hline
\textbf{ID} & \textbf{Auto-Generated question} & \textbf{Closest question in the dataset}\\
\hline
1 & Let $A$ be the matrix $\begin{bmatrix} 1 & 2 & 3 \\ 4 & 5 & 6 \\ 7 & 8 & 9 \end{bmatrix}$ Find the determinant of $A^2 + A^3.$ & 
If $\det A   2$ and $\det B   12,$ then find $\det (AB).$
\\
\hline
2 & Let $A$ be a matrix such that $\det A   -1.$ Find the determinant of $A^2.$ & 
If $\det A   5,$ then find $\det (A^3).$
\\
\hline
3 & Let $A$ be a matrix such that $A^2   I$ and $A^3   I.$ Find the determinant of $A.$&
If $\det A   5,$ then find $\det (A^3).$
\\
\hline
4 & Let $A$ be the matrix $\begin{bmatrix} 1 & 1 \\ 1 & 1 \end{bmatrix}$ and $B$ be the matrix $\begin{bmatrix} 1 & 1 \\ 1 & -1 \end{bmatrix}.$ Find the determinant of $AB$ and $BA.$& 
If $\det A   2$ and $\det B   12,$ then find $\det (AB).$
\\ 
\hline
5 & Let $A$ be a matrix such that $\det A   -1.$ Find the determinant of $A^{-1}$ if it exists.& 
If $\det A   5,$ then find $\det (A^3).$
\\
\hline
6 & Let $A$ be a matrix such that $\det A   -1.$ Find the determinant of $A^2.$&
If $\det A   5,$ then find $\det (A^3).$
\\
\hline
7 & Let $A$ be a point on the unit circle in the complex plane, and let $B$ be a point on the unit circle in the complex plane. If $A   e^{i\pi/6}$ and $B   e^{i\pi/3},$ then find $AB.$& 
If the six solutions of $x^6-64$ are written in the form $a+bi$, where $a$ and $b$ are real, find the product of those solutions with $a>0.$
\\
\hline
8 & Find the equation of the plane that passes through the points $(1,2,3)$, $(2,3,4)$, and $(3,4,5).$ & Let $S$ be a region in the plane with area 10. When we apply the matrix $\begin{bmatrix} 2 & 1 \\ 7 & -3 \end{bmatrix}$to $S,$ we obtain the region $S'.$   Find the area of $S'.$
\\
\hline
9 & Find the angle between the vectors $\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}$ and $\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}.$ & 
If $\|A\|   3$ and $\|B\|   6,$ then find $(A + B) \cdot (A - B).$
\\
\hline
10 & Find the number of ordered pairs $(x,y)$ such that $x^2 + y^2   1$ and $x^2 + y^2 + 2xy   1.$ & 
If the six solutions of $x^6-64$ are written in the form $a+bi$, where $a$ and $b$ are real, find the product of those solutions with $a > 0.$
\\ \hline
\end{longtable}
title: A Neural Network Solves, Explains, and Generates University Math Problems by Program Synthesis and Few-Shot Learning at Human Level
